<HEADLINE>
70% OF TAIWAN ADULTS EAT OUT FREQUENTLY: SURVEY
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  June 1 (CNA) 06/01/07  13:45:59 (By Y.F. Low)
</P>
<P>
Seventy percent of Taiwan adults eat out frequently, with a
higher ratio of men doing so than women, according to the results
of a recent survey released by the Global Views Monthly magazine.
</P>
<P>
The magazine estimated that 3.3 million of Taiwan adults eat out
everyday.
</P>
<P>
The trend is most common among those in the 20-29 age group,
which includes students and young office workers, with more than
35 percent of people in this group not having meals at home
everyday, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
Citing tallies from the Directorate-General of Budget, Accounting
and Statistics, the magazine noted that each Taiwan family spent
some NT$50,000 (US$1,515) on average eating out last year,
meaning that the total spending by Taiwan's more than 7 million
households on eating out amounted to NT$36 billion for the year.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that lunch is the meal that the largest
percentage of respondents enjoy outside the home frequently, with
78.7 percent doing so, followed by breakfast, with 66.8 percent
of respondents usually eating this meal outside the home.
</P>
<P>
As to the places where people eat out for lunch, 59.6 percent of
respondents mentioned boxed lunch sellers, noodle eateries and
snack bars.  Other popular choices  mentioned  included
cafeterias, restaurants and luncheonettes, as well as roadside
food stands and food wagons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the oyster omelet was selected by the largest number
of respondents as the snack best representing Taiwan, followed by
pearl milk tea, oyster vermicelli, stinky tofu and braised pork
rice. Other items mentioned included rice meat balls, rice
dumplings, tan-tsai noodles, beef noodles, small steamer buns,
rice noodles, and bowl cakes, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted via telephone from May 4-9 on 500 men and
500 women around Taiwan, is said to have a margin of error of
plus or minus 3.1 percent.
</P>
